Title: 
 Capital Structure and the Market for Corporate Control: The Defensive Role of Debt Financing.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1391-1409
Issue: 4
Volume: 46
Year: 1991
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 A capital structure theory based on corporate control considerations is
 presented. The optimal debt level balances a decrease in the probability
 of acquisition against a higher share of the synergy for the target's
 shareholders. This leads to the following implications: (1) the
 probability of firms becoming acquisition targets decreases with their
 leverage; (2) acquirers' share of the total equity gain increases with
 targets' leverage; (3) when acquisitions are initiated, targets' stock
 price, targets' debt value, and acquirers' firm value increase; and (4)
 during the acquisition, target firms' stock price changes further; the
 expected change is zero and the variance decreases with targets' debt
 level.


