Title: 
 A Theory of Workouts and the Effects of Reorganization Law.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1189-1222
Issue: 4
Volume: 46
Year: 1991
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 The authors present a model of a financially distressed firm with
 outstanding bank debt and public debt. Coordination problems among public
 debtholders introduce investment inefficiencies in the workout process. In
 most cases, these inefficiencies are not mitigated by the ability of firms
 to buy back their public debt with cash and other securities--the only
 feasible way that firms can restructure their public debt. The authors
 show that Chapter 11 reorganization law increases investment and they
 characterize the types of corporate financial structures for which this
 increased investment enhances efficiency.


