Title: 
 Order Form and Information in Securities Markets.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 905-27
Issue: 3
Volume: 46
Year: 1991
Month:  July 
Abstract:

 This paper examines the effects of price-contingent orders on security
 prices. The authors show that a market maker who knows the type and
 composition of trades will set larger spreads and adjust prices faster
 than if price-contingent orders were not allowed. Because traders have
 rational expectations over the book, the authors demonstrate that
 uncertainty over order type reduces the variance of prices but with a
 corresponding loss in price informativeness. They also show that the
 sequence property of price-contingent orders increases the probability of
 large price movements. This distinction between variance and episodic
 price volatility has important policy implications.


