Title: 
 Animal Spirits, Margin Requirements, and Stock Price Volatility.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 717-31
Issue: 2
Volume: 46
Year: 1991
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 A simple overlapping generations model is used to characterize the
 effects of initial margin requirements in the volatility of risky asset
 prices. Investors are assumed to exhibit heterogenous preferences for
 risk-bearing, the distribution of which evolves stochastically across
 generations. This framework is used to show that imposing a binding
 initial marginal requirement may either increase or decrease stock price
 volatility, depending upon the microeconomic structure behind fluctuations
 in economywide average risk-bearing propensity. The ambiguous effect on
 volatility similarly arises when the source of heterogeneity is noise
 trader beliefs.


