Abstract:

 The authors characterize the exchange of financial claims from risky
 swaps. These transfers are among three groups: shareholders, debtholders,
 and the swap counterparty. From this analysis, the authors derive
 equilibrium swap rates and relate them to debt market spreads. They then
 show that equilibrium swaps in perfect markets transfer wealth from
 shareholders to debtholders. In a simplified case, the authors obtain
 closed-form solutions for the value of the default risk in the swap. For
 interest-rate swaps, they obtain numerical solutions for the equilibrium
 swap rate, including default risk. The authors compare these with
 equilibrium debt market default risk spreads.


