Title: 
 Patterns of Productivity in the Finance Literature: A Study of the Bibliometric Distributions.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 301-09
Issue: 1
Volume: 45
Year: 1990
Month:  March 
Abstract:

 This study finds a bibliometric regularity in the finance literature that
 the number of authors publishing n papers is about 1/n(superscript "c") of
 those publishing one paper. The authors find that the finance literature
 conforms very well to the inverse square law(c = 2) if data are taken from
 a large collection of journals. When applied to individual finance
 journals, they find that values of c range from 1.95 to 3.26. They also
 find that top-rated journals have higher concentrations among their
 contributors. This implies that the phenomenon "success breeds success" is
 more common in higher-quality publications.


