Abstract:

 Prior studies report lower issue costs for shelf registered debt and
 conclude that the benefits of increased underwriter competition can be
 realized by those firms using this registration procedure. This study
 reexamines the purported superiority of issuing debt via shelf
 registration, and finds that the savings in issue costs displayed by
 earlier studies can be attributed to a self-selection bias and not the
 method of registration.


