Title: 
 Expectations and the Treasury Bill-Federal Funds Rate Spread over Recent Monetary Policy Regimes.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 467-77
Issue: 2
Volume: 45
Year: 1990
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 This paper shows that the spread between the three-month Treasury bill
 and the federal funds rate has significant predictive power for the future
 change in the federal funds rate during the volatile nonborrowed reserves
 operating regime, but it has less and no predictive power during the
 borrowed reserves regime and the federal funds targeting regime,
 respectively. These findings suggest that Treasury bill rates forecast
 future federal funds rates most accurately when the Federal Reserve
 follows a well-defined rule that does not smooth the impact of shocks on
 the federal funds rate.


